    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-11-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-11-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <head>64. National Security Study Memorandum 142<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d64fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–188, National Security Study Memoranda, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM_1">NSSM</gloss> 142. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-11-19">November 19, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Rhodesia</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a review be made of the implications for U.S.
                    policy of a British-Rhodesian settlement acknowledging Rhodesia’s independence
                    and calling for the termination of sanctions. The study should also deal with
                    the implication of failure of the present negotiations to produce a political
                    settlement. The study should, inter alia: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Assess the probable reaction in the United Nations and elsewhere to a
                            British-Rhodesian agreement and the issues which this development is
                            likely to pose for U.S. policy.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Assess the probable reaction in the <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss>
                            and elsewhere to failure of U.K.–Rhodesia negotiations and the issues
                            which such a development is likely to pose for U.S. policy including the
                            sanctions program.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Examine the legal, political, and economic implications involved in
                            (a) U.S. recognition of an independent Rhodesia, and (b) the
                            establishing of diplomatic or consular relations therewith.</item>
                        <pb facs="0199" n="160" xml:id="pg_160"/>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Identify the probable consequences of each possible U.S. action for
                            our immediate and longer term interests in the United Nations and for
                            our bilateral relations with the countries primarily concerned.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The study should be prepared by the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>
                    Interdepartmental Group for Africa and should be submitted to the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Senior Review Group by December 13, 1971.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d64fn2">In a July 18, 1972, memorandum to Kennedy, Fred Rondon
                        wrote: “<gloss target="#t_NSSM_1">NSSM</gloss> 142 on Rhodesia was
                        predicated upon a successful British settlement with <persName
                            corresp="#p_SID_1">Ian Smith</persName>. It did not come about. With no
                        early prospects for British recognition of Rhodesia, I see no need for us to
                        further consider the policy options in the <gloss target="#t_NSSM_1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 142 study.” (Ibid., Box H–181, National Security Study
                        Memoranda, <gloss target="#t_NSSM_1">NSSM</gloss> 115) The study is ibid.,
                        Box H–188, National Security Study Memoranda, <gloss target="#t_NSSM_1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 115.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
